04004nam a22006495i 9780292793422DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927934227 a10.7560/7210812doi  a(DE-B1597)587933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1234b.P55 2010 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6582221 aPick, Zuzana M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstructing the Image of the Mexican Revolution :bCinema and the Archive /cZuzana M. Pick. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (265 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Visualizing and Romancing the Revolution -- tChapter 1 The Revolution as Media Event: Documentary Image and the Archive -- tChapter 2 Historicity and the Archive: Reconstruction and Appropriation -- tChapter 3 Pancho Villa on Two Sides of the Border -- tChapter 4 Avant-Garde Gestures and Nationalist Images of Mexico in Eisenstein’s Unfinished Project -- tChapter 5 Reconfiguring the Revolution: Celebrity and Melodrama -- tChapter 6 The Aesthetics of Spectacle -- tChapter 7 Competing Narratives and Converging Visions -- tConclusion. Thoughts on Working with the Archive -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith a cast ranging from Pancho Villa to Dolores del Río and Tina Modotti, Constructing the Image of the Mexican Revolution demonstrates the crucial role played by Mexican and foreign visual artists in revolutionizing Mexico's twentieth-century national iconography. Investigating the convergence of cinema, photography, painting, and other graphic arts in this process, Zuzana Pick illuminates how the Mexican Revolution's timeline (1910–1917) corresponds with the emergence of media culture and modernity. Drawing on twelve foundational films from Que Viva Mexico! (1931–1932) to And Starring Pancho Villa as Himself (2003), Pick proposes that cinematic images reflect the image repertoire produced during the revolution, often playing on existing nationalist themes or on folkloric motifs designed for export. Ultimately illustrating the ways in which modernism reinvented existing signifiers of national identity, Constructing the Image of the Mexican Revolution unites historicity, aesthetics, and narrative to enrich our understanding of Mexicanidad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion pictureszMexicoxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar filmszMexicoxHistory and criticism. 0aWar filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72108140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793422/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK